<h1>Problem 1649 - Folklore, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(P(x)\) be a polynomial with real coefficients and \(a_1, a_2, \dots\) be a strictly increasing sequence of positive integers such that \(a_n < P(n)\) for all positive integers \(n\). Prove that there exist infinitely many primes that divide an element of the sequence.</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class=skib>
<p>Suppose the prime set of \(\{a_n\}\) is finite. Let the set be \(P = \{p_1, p_2, \dots, p_k\}\). So every element \(a_n\) is of the form \(p_1^{\alpha_1} p_2^{\alpha_2} \dots p_k^{\alpha_k}\). First let us count the number of numbers of this form below \(P(n)\) for some large \(n\). If it's below \(n\) then we are done. Suppose \(r\) is the degree of \(P\). We take \(n\) sufficiently large so that we can approximate \(P(n)\) by \((a_r + \epsilon) n^r\). To be fair, I don't expect this to work out because this does not use the strictly increasing condition at all. Wait also counting this is pretty hard, so I'll just try it for \(2\) primes \(p > q\). 
\[\log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r/p) + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r/p^2) + \dots + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r/p^{\log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r)})\]
\[\sim \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) - \log_q(p) + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) - 2\log_q(p) + \dots + \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) - \log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r)\log_q(p)\]
\[\sim \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) \log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) - \frac{\log_q(p)\log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r)(\log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) + 1)}{2} \sim \frac{\log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r) \log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r)}{2}\]
\[\sim \frac{(\log_q(a_r + \epsilon) + r\log_q(n))(\log_p(a_r + \epsilon) + r\log_p(n))}{2} <<< n\]
Well, there's that. Now, if we add another prime \(s\) to roughly this expression, we get the sum 
\[\sum_{i=0}^{\log_s((a_r+\epsilon)n^r)} i \log_q((a_r +\epsilon)n^r/s^i) \log_p((a_r +\epsilon)n^r/s^i) < \log_s((a_r+\epsilon)n^r) \log_s((a_r+\epsilon)n^r) \log_p((a_r+\epsilon)n^r) \log_q((a_r+\epsilon)n^r)\]
Basically, the idea is that \((c\log(n))^k < n\) for large \(n\) for some fixed \(k\) (polynomial growth is slower than exponential growth, \(n\) is exponential for \(\log(n)\)).</p>
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Problems can be misleading. Additional information might be contained. Work on something simpler or different to see what goes wrong. In this case, the strictly increasing condition is only to ensure distinctness.</p>
